Dataset:¶

FitBit Fitness Tracker Data

https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/arashnic/fitbit

It contains data from survey respondents who were Fitbit users between March 12, 2016 and May 12, 2016. The data includes various measures of physical activity, such as total distance covered, total steps taken, average intensity of activity, time spent in 4 varying levels of activity (sedentary, light, fair, very). There are also records of the respondents' sleep activity, including their time spent in bed and time spent sleeping, both in minutes.

Objective 1:¶

Understanding Sleep Patterns: The primary objective of conducting a linear regression analysis on Fitbit data is to gain a comprehensive understanding of the relationship between sleep activity and various physical and lifestyle factors. By exploring how sleep quality (dependent variable) is influenced by independent variables such as Activity Score, Total Steps, Total Distance, Calories, and Average Intensity, we aim to uncover patterns and insights that can inform individuals about the impact of their daily activities on their sleep. This analysis will enable us to quantitatively assess which factors contribute positively or negatively to sleep quality and identify areas for potential improvement.¶

Objective 2:¶

Predictive Modeling and Health Optimization: Another key objective is to develop a predictive model that can accurately forecast sleep activity based on the selected independent variables. This predictive capability will empower individuals to proactively manage their sleep patterns by adjusting their physical activity levels, caloric intake, and other lifestyle factors. The model can serve as a valuable tool for making data-driven decisions to optimize sleep quality and overall health. Ultimately, the goal is to provide actionable insights and personalized recommendations that promote better sleep habits, leading to improved well-being and quality of life. Through this analysis, we aim to bridge the gap between lifestyle choices and sleep outcomes, offering individuals a data-driven approach to achieving healthier and more restful sleep patterns.¶

Stakeholders:¶

Fitbit users, the primary stakeholders, can use analysis insights to optimize their health by adjusting daily routines. Healthcare professionals and wellness coaches are secondary stakeholders who can provide data-driven guidance to patients and clients for improved sleep and physical activity, enhancing overall well-being.¶

The areas of interest in the data lie within the differnet levels of activity Light, Fairly, and Very Active Minutes, as well as the Intensity Levels. 3) Data Cleaning:¶

Below we cleaned and then merged the three csv files. We then removed the columns that we found to be unnecessary for this particular linear regression model. This will give a final combined dataset that is much more manageable to work with.¶

1) Since there were multiple entries per day for each individual regarding the activity intensity, we decided to aggregate the data for the intensity level and consolidate them all into one day. This allows us to then use this newly created dataset to merge with the other two csv file, which only have one entry per day.¶

In [ ]:
averaged_data_df <- aggregate(cbind(TotalIntensity, AverageIntensity) ~ Id + Date, data = activity_intensity_df, FUN = mean)

2) Below we weighted the values of activity per day and create a standard "activity score" as a basis of comparison. Main ideation for modeling this variable was taken from Page 9 of: https://www.fitabase.com/media/1748/fitabasedatadictionary.pdf

Where it essentially shows that they model increasing intensity in activity using integer values from 0 to 3

In [ ]:
subset_FitBit_data_df$Activity_Score <- (3 * subset_FitBit_data_df$VeryActiveMinutes) +
  (2 * subset_FitBit_data_df$FairlyActiveMinutes) + (1 * subset_FitBit_data_df$LightlyActiveMinutes)

3) Below we converted total sleep minutes into hours, and then created some "bins" to group our Activity Score and Hours Asleep. This grouping helps with visualizing the data below. We then printed the dataset to ensure these adaptations worked.¶

In [ ]:
subset_FitBit_data_df$TotalHoursAsleep <- subset_FitBit_data_df$TotalMinutesAsleep/60

6) Response Variable:¶

The response variable "Total hours of sleep" refers to the main area of interest our analysis. It represents the number of hours a person sleeps during a day. Researchers and analysts often study "Total hours of sleep" to understand how various factors, such as physical activity, lifestyle choices, and health conditions may influence a person's sleep patterns. By examining this response variable, we aim to uncover insights into sleep behavior, identify trends or correlations, and make predictions about sleep duration. Hopefully this analysis will help to improve our understanding of sleep-related factors that affect overall health. Our goal is to analyze whether there is a positive impact on sleep as a result of workouts or physical activity.¶

8) Simple Linear Regression:¶

First, we created 5 different simple linear regressions using 5 different independent variables in order to find a relationship between them and Percentage_Asleep. The 5 independent variables are:

  1. Activity_Score
  2. TotalSteps
  3. Total Intensity
  4. Very Active Minutes
  5. Fairly Active Minutes
  6. Lightly Active Minutes

1) Total Hours Asleep vs Activity Score¶

  • The summary of activityModel and graph below shows a negative relationship between Total Hours Asleep and Activity Score. It can be seen that the more active a person is, the less sleep they may actually have compared to a less active person. R-squared value of 0.01571 (or 1.571%) suggests that activity is not a strong predictor of the number of hours of sleep.
In [ ]:
activityModel <- lm(TotalHoursAsleep ~ Activity_Score, subset_FitBit_data_df)
summary(activityModel)

library(ggplot2)

plot <- ggplot(data = subset_FitBit_data_df, aes(x = Activity_Score , y = TotalHoursAsleep)) +
  geom_point(color = "darkblue", shape = 19) +
  geom_abline(intercept = activityModel$coefficients[1], slope = activityModel$coefficients[2], color = "red", linetype = "solid") +
  labs(x = "Activity Score", y = "Total Hours Asleep") +
  ggtitle("Relationship Between Activity Score and Total Hours Asleep") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text = element_text(size = 12), axis.title = element_text(size = 14),
        panel.background = element_rect(fill = "grey"))


print(plot)

3) Here, we created polynomial regression model using the 2 variables with the best correlations to total hours slept as seen in the previous multiple regression models. Summary:¶

Upon comparing the simple regression results with the multiple regression results, several insights can be taken. In the simple regressions, individual predictors like Activity Score, Total Steps, Total Intensity, Very Active Minutes, Fairly Active Minutes, and Lightly Active Minutes were assessed for their relationship with Total Hours Asleep. Among them, the model involving Fairly Active Minutes had the strongest relationship with Total Hours Asleep, as evidenced by the highest R-squared value of 0.0598. However, when considering the multiple regression models, the predictors were combined in various configurations to examine their joint impact. The R-squared values in these models, ranging from 0.06076 to 0.07335, are generally higher than those in the simple regressions, indicating that combining predictors can better explain the variability in sleep hours. The model incorporating Fairly Active Minutes, Total Steps, their squared terms, and interaction term had the highest R-squared value among multiple regressions, suggesting it explains the most variance in Total Hours Asleep.¶

Project Report¶

Introduction: After looking into the data collected by Fitbit. We have found a better look at what aspects of daily activity have on the amount of sleep a person gets.¶

Simple Regression Analysis: Initially, we analyzed each activity separately. This means we looked at factors like total steps, exercise intensity, and the various minutes of activity throughout the day. We wanted to see which single factor might be the biggest influencer on sleep duration. See plot below for R-squared values of each of our regression models.¶

Moving to Multiple Factors: After comparing only single variables to the hours slept, it was best to move on to a multiple linear regression model. This is where we started to gain more insight into what may predict better sleep. We have three different multiple linear regression models and one is a polynomial model.¶

Improved Results: Combining certain activities gave a slightly clearer picture of sleep patterns. When we paired "fairly active" minutes with total steps, we saw a stronger connection, with R-squared values ranging between 0.06076 and 0.07335.¶

The Best Combination: Of all the mixtures we tried, the duo of "fairly active" minutes and total steps stood out. Together, they seemed to be the best predictors of sleep duration. This combination gave us the most insight into daily activity and its impact on sleep patterns.¶

Limitations: While there is a strong correlations with fairly active minutes and sleep, the implications of the number of individuals in the study may have an impact that skews the results. From earlier, we can see that the majority of indivuals fell into the fairly active catagory. This would suggest that our models are heavily weighted in that direction.¶

Bigger Picture: Regardless of the amount of indivduals or their grouping, it is very evident that activity has a significant impact on your sleep. Sometimes this may be more conterintuitive than you may think. Some suggestions state that the higher you activity, the better you'll sleep. From this dataset, that doesn;t seem to be the case.¶

Conclusion: What's the takeaway? Being active undoubtedly plays a role in how well and long you sleep. But how active? This might be something that you would want to take a closer look at for yourself. Paying attention to how your individual activity rate impacts your sleep, may be a better approach than just following the normal thought that the more active you are the better your sleep will be. We suggest that taking a more personal approach, and applying our analysis to your own data may be the best was for you to take your sleep into your own hand, and determine what activity levels are optimal for you.¶

Future Study Recommendation In the future, to build a more comprehensive analysis and derive implications between sleep and physical activity, a larger dataset will a more even spread of data and values would be needed. Having said that, it would be extremely difficult to cherry pick a range of different individuals with a varying levels of physical activity and sleep patterns.¶
